B29.value: B6 simulates wind speed changes, by using a function called RANDBETWEEN(). This function gives back random numbers.

B30.value: B11 until B15 calculate values based on the current change of wind. Using simple spreadsheet formulars it is possible to calculate the wind speed and the angle of the blades.

B31.value: B20 uses the stream function MQTT.PUBLISH to send data to a MQTT Broker. This data is then available under the topic in B19.

B32.value: The blades of the turbine in this simulation are shapes. As everything in Streamsheets, these shapes are based on a function. Parameters of a function can be static or set via cell references and this way made dynamic.

B33.value: In this szenario all shapes use the x & y parameters from cells B22 and B23. Further, the blades of the turbine use the cell value from B13 to calculate the blade positioning in the "angle" parameter.

B30.value: Drag&Drop payload elements to link your data stream to the sheet (e.g. A5&B5). The adjacent functions use this data as input for their calculations.

B31.value: This x/y chart displays a data history of the power output of the windmill. The TIMEAGGREGATE() function in B6 stores speed values for one minute and serves as data source for the chart. Charts can also use regular data ranges to display data as seen in the second chart. The chart below uses the range A14:B24.

B32.value: The function TABLE.UPDATE() is used to generate the table in A14:B24.
